This paper is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category as it focuses on cyber security intelligence related to DNS Amplification DDoS activities. It also involves the detection, prevention, assessment, mitigation, and attribution of such activities, which are all related to cryptography and security. 

The paper also involves network-layer and flow-based insights, which are related to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. 

The use of certain DDoS parameters to detect attacks suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category, as it involves the analysis of network data to extract insights. 

The paper's use of empirical evaluation and the proposed approach's exploitation of DDoS parameters suggest that it may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's focus on data analysis and the use of real darknet data suggest that it may also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category.
